## Special Considerations

### Citizenship through Marriage

- Spouses of U.S. citizens can apply after 3 years of permanent residency and must have lived in marital union with the citizen spouse during that time.
- Physical presence must be at least 18 months out of the 3 years.
- Proof of spouse’s citizenship, marriage validity, termination of prior marriages, and cohabitation must be submitted.
- Applicants must meet all other naturalization requirements ([CitizenPath, 2021](https://citizenpath.com/applying-for-citizenship-through-marriage/)).

### Citizenship through Military Service

- Military personnel who served honorably during periods of hostility (since September 11, 2001) may apply immediately without meeting residency requirements.
- Peacetime service members must have served at least one year and meet other criteria.
- Filing fees are waived, and special forms (e.g., Form N-426) are required ([USCIS, 2020](https://www.uscis.gov/military/naturalization-through-military-service)).

### Citizenship through Parents

- Children born abroad to U.S. citizen parents may acquire citizenship automatically or through application, depending on parents’ marital status and physical presence in the U.S.
- Adopted children may also acquire citizenship if certain custody and residency requirements are met ([USCIS, 2020](https://www.uscis.gov/citizenship/learn-about-citizenship/citizenship-through-parents)).

